g.text: This document contains the section contours of a rim used in the construction of a RingRap 3D printer.
This instruction page will walk you through adding a new contour for your
to change the contour in the openSCAD model.

text.tspan: 1: Open the layers tool (Ctrl+Shift+L), and make a new layer ( ). Name that layer with a
unique description of you rim pofile Make a rough sketch of rim contour, the example to
the left is one i have taken from a quick google search. NOTE: Layer names must not use

flowRoot.flowPara: 2: Trace the modle using the pen tool in inkscape( ) simply click along the contour, if you click and hold you can make curves, you can adust the angle of the curves by using the node tool( ) It is important to note where the bottom of the rim's bead is. I do that with a seperate marking, the group the contour and marking temporarily (Ctrl + g). My contour was drawn in show and the maker was drawn in blue.

4:Now that the profile has been drawn, we need to convert it to only straight lines, We do that by using the node tool ( ), and selecting the modle, then selecting the nodes that have a curve applied, then click the add nodes button ( ). In the end a straight line will be drawn between each of the nod'\es, when you feel that you have enough points to apoximate the curve clicke the "turn nodes into corner button" ( ) twice. NOTE, it is possible to place nodes too close together and openSCAD will not be able to render the object If that happens, delete some of the tightly packed nodes.
3: Resize the modle in the x and y dimentions to match the rim using the select tool ( ). In m this will be W=35mm H=22mm.
5: Rotate the obect into a inner contour down orientation using the select tool.

6: move the object so the width is centered on zero and the bottom of the bead marker is a 0 on the height axis. Onece you are finished you should ungroup the marker and contour and delete the marker. To note this i ungrouped and changed the marker to red.
7: Save the SVG, this will be easier to edit later then, "Save as" a DXF make sure the DXF name is rim_section_contour.dxf
8: in the "Build_specifications.scad" file change the "cur_rim_shape=" variable to be your layer name in double quotes followed by a ;
9: Now when you run "Ring_Rap_OpenSCAD_remix.scad" you will have you shiney new controur instead of the dusty old original.
